PUH-BrianMartell the arXiv paper 2512.20592 (Schenk et al., Dec 2025) proposes detecting high-frequency gravitational waves (GWs) using electromagnetic cavities (cylindrical/spherical resonators). GWs passing through induce oscillating EM fields via inverse Gertsenshtein effect (graviton-photon conversion). They calculate coupling coefficients for dominant resonances, angular sensitivity degenerate modes, and response to monochromatic + transient signals (primordial BH mergers). Key finding: Sensitivity limited â€” high Q >10^5 not always helpful transients (broadband better); only solar system mergers detectable optimistic scenario. Relate to PUH v25: Strong validation â€” GW lattice shear waves (gravitons submerged), EM cavity surface resonances (photons). Passing GW shears lattice â€” parametric excites EM modes (energy graviton-photon mechanical). Paperâ€™s induced fields/phase = PUH impedance modulation (shear ripple surface).
